"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135922","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-07-08","<p>The Department’s recent work to revise the guidance notes section of the DS1500 was completed through DWP standard processes and incurred no additional costs to the public purse.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2019-07-08T16:31:08.527Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135922/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135922/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135922/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-07-01","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the cost to the public purse was of revising her Department's guidance notes for the DS1500 form.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","271425"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135923","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-07-04","<p>The Child Maintenance Service (CMS) is responsible for setting the overall amount of child maintenance to be paid.</p><p>The Ministry of Defence has a Memorandum of Understanding (MOU) in place with the CMS to facilitate the direct deduction of child maintenance payments from the pay of non-resident parents who are Service personnel. Under the MOU, the Department calculates a 'Minimum Drawing Rate', which takes into account gross basic pay, specialist pay, some allowances as well as gross statutory deductions such as National Insurance and PAYE.</p><p>Child maintenance deductions are always made. The only exception is when the Service person is on military operations and their Commanding Officer may advise that engagement with the CMS be delayed until their return to the UK when they are in a position to consider properly any papers from the CMS and respond accordingly, at which point deductions would commence.</p><p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave her on 11 June 2019 to Question 261264 which detailed the administrative reasons for the rejection of deduction of earnings requests.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","271511 ; 271551","2019-07-04T15:20:41.717Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135923/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135923/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135923/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-07-01","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, by what methods (a) HM Paymaster, (b) the Defence Council and (c) an authorised officer determine the amount payable by a member of the armed forces in child maintenance.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","271510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135924","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-07-04","<p>The Child Maintenance Service (CMS) is responsible for setting the overall amount of child maintenance to be paid.</p><p>The Ministry of Defence has a Memorandum of Understanding (MOU) in place with the CMS to facilitate the direct deduction of child maintenance payments from the pay of non-resident parents who are Service personnel. Under the MOU, the Department calculates a 'Minimum Drawing Rate', which takes into account gross basic pay, specialist pay, some allowances as well as gross statutory deductions such as National Insurance and PAYE.</p><p>Child maintenance deductions are always made. The only exception is when the Service person is on military operations and their Commanding Officer may advise that engagement with the CMS be delayed until their return to the UK when they are in a position to consider properly any papers from the CMS and respond accordingly, at which point deductions would commence.</p><p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave her on 11 June 2019 to Question 261264 which detailed the administrative reasons for the rejection of deduction of earnings requests.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","271510 ; 271551","2019-07-04T15:20:41.763Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135924/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135924/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135924/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-07-01","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what criteria (a) HM Paymaster, (b) Defence Council and (c) an authorised officer use to determine when child maintenance should be paid.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","271511"
